        <h2>2. Procore — Best for commercial scheduling</h2>
        <p><strong>Pricing:</strong> Custom (contact sales)</p>

        <p>Procore's scheduling module integrates with industry standards like Microsoft Project and Primavera P6, which is what large commercial projects already use. The lookahead scheduling feature lets superintendents plan 3–6 week windows at a detailed task level, separate from the master schedule.</p>

        <p><strong>Scheduling-specific strengths:</strong></p>
        <ul>
          <li>Lookahead scheduling (3-week, 4-week planning windows)</li>
          <li>Baseline comparison to track schedule variance over time</li>
          <li>Integration with Microsoft Project and Primavera P6</li>
          <li>Scheduling tied to RFIs, submittals, and punch items</li>
          <li>Multi-party access for GC, subs, and owners</li>
        </ul>

        <p><strong>Limitations:</strong></p>
        <ul>
          <li>Significant learning curve — scheduling module requires training</li>
          <li>Overkill and overpriced for residential or small commercial</li>
          <li>Best value only when using Procore's full platform</li>
        </ul>

        <h2>3. Fieldwire — Best field-level scheduling for subs</h2>
        <p><strong>Pricing:</strong> Free (3 projects) · Pro $19/user/mo · Business $29/user/mo · Business Plus $54/user/mo</p>

        <p>Fieldwire doesn't do Gantt scheduling in the traditional sense, but it does task management tied to actual plan locations — which is what field teams actually need. Foremen and subs can see their tasks for the day, what's coming next, and what's blocked.</p>

        <p><strong>Scheduling-specific strengths:</strong></p>
        <ul>
          <li>Task scheduling at the room/location level — not just "Phase 2"</li>
          <li>Offline functionality — works without internet on job sites</li>
          <li>Free plan covers small teams and simple projects</li>
          <li>Designed for the foreman, not the office</li>
        </ul>

        <p><strong>Limitations:</strong></p>
        <ul>
          <li>No true Gantt scheduling or dependency tracking</li>
          <li>Not a standalone project management solution</li>
          <li>Per-user pricing adds up for larger crews</li>
        </ul>

        <h2>4. JobTread — Best value scheduling for small GCs</h2>
        <p><strong>Pricing:</strong> Basic $99/mo · Standard $199/mo · Pro $349/mo</p>

        <p>JobTread offers solid scheduling within a complete job management platform. It's not as advanced as Buildertrend's Gantt system, but for a contractor managing 5–10 projects at a time without a dedicated project coordinator, it handles day-to-day scheduling well.</p>

        <p><strong>Scheduling-specific strengths:</strong></p>
        <ul>
          <li>Project timeline view with milestones</li>
          <li>Task assignments with due dates and sub access</li>
          <li>Clean interface that's fast to learn</li>
          <li>Included in a complete PM platform at a fraction of Buildertrend's cost</li>
        </ul>

        <p><strong>Limitations:</strong></p>
        <ul>
          <li>Less sophisticated dependency logic than Buildertrend</li>
          <li>Multi-project scheduling view is simpler</li>
        </ul>

        <h2>Dedicated scheduling tools worth knowing</h2>

        <h3>Microsoft Project</h3>
        <p>The industry standard for complex project scheduling, particularly in commercial construction. Powerful, but expensive (~$30/user/mo) and requires significant training. Most useful when your clients or GCs require it as a deliverable.</p>

        <h3>Primavera P6</h3>
        <p>Oracle's enterprise scheduling tool, used on massive infrastructure and commercial projects. Extremely powerful, extremely complex. Only relevant for large commercial GCs or specialty contractors who need CPM scheduling.</p>

        <h3>BuilderPad / ConstructionOnline</h3>
        <p>Mid-market alternatives worth evaluating if Buildertrend and JobTread don't fit. Less market presence but solid scheduling features.</p>

        <h2>How to choose construction scheduling software</h2>

        <h3>Are you residential or commercial?</h3>
        <p>The scheduling requirements differ significantly. Residential scheduling is about managing subs, owner selections, and keeping a home on track. Commercial scheduling involves critical path method (CPM), baseline tracking, multi-party coordination, and contractual milestones. Choose tools designed for your segment.</p>

        <h3>Do you need full project management or just scheduling?</h3>
        <p>If scheduling is your only gap, Fieldwire or even a well-structured Google Calendar might suffice. If you also need budgeting, change orders, and client communication, invest in a full platform like Buildertrend or JobTread so everything integrates.</p>

        <h3>How many projects are you running simultaneously?</h3>
        <p>1–3 active projects: JobTread or Fieldwire is sufficient. 5–20+ residential projects: Buildertrend's multi-project view becomes essential. Large commercial portfolio: Procore.</p>

        <h2>Frequently asked questions</h2>

        <h3>Can I use Excel for construction scheduling?</h3>
        <p>Many contractors still do, and it works for simple projects. The problems emerge when tasks cascade: a delay in framing requires manually adjusting every downstream task. Dedicated scheduling software automates this and saves hours of update time per delay event.</p>

        <h3>What's the difference between Gantt charts and critical path scheduling?</h3>
        <p>Gantt charts show tasks on a timeline with dependencies. Critical path method (CPM) identifies which sequence of tasks, if delayed, will delay the entire project. Buildertrend uses Gantt with dependency tracking; Procore and Primavera P6 support full CPM analysis.</p>

        <h3>Do subs need their own account to see the schedule?</h3>
        <p>In Buildertrend, subs get free access at all plan levels — you can add them without extra cost. In Fieldwire, per-user pricing applies. JobTread varies by plan tier. Always check sub-user costs before committing to a platform.</p>

